OK.. I'll buy the one comment that "speed skill" can be on a once a day timer like harm touch or lay of hands.. however, they you don't have to increase that skill either and it's fixed upon the level of the character instead with no skill points given.<P>As for camo? it may step on the toes of a rogue's ability in some circumstances, but not all.  As for the high end game.  I would much rather have a "class" on raids, especially failing ones, that can go in undetected by ANY mob and pull the corpse out with speed and reliablity.  Infact if anything this would actually step on the toes of those classes that summon corpses (but NO coffin needed) The trade of is that Once you summon corpse of a fallen guild member you are visiable again but you do have the hitpoints and speed to beet ass back to the zone and drop off the corpse.  I only suggest this as a high end alternative in being needed in tough zones.<P>The intimidate would not allow us to fear kite.  As I said if you are sucessful to an experience mob (50% approx) you are unable to hit it without it turning and attacking. The flash of light spell does NOT do this.  BTW. if you use flash of light while both you and pet are fighting and you back off.. the mob does not turn and run, he stays planted where he is figting your pet.  So what purpose does this spell have (besides lowering it's ATK rating by 5 points)..<P>The shell skill is similar to FD but with slower reload and 10 minute delay as one person suggested.<P>I chose these line of skills because they are similar but different in many reguards to what is currently occupied by other classes and races.<P>I did not choose any offensive skills because that would be overpowering unless you do something with the pet/master combo.<BR>A pet that hits for up to 3 or 4 times and a BST that adds in his dual weilding and kick (plus spells) is enough damage.  To add in more offensive damage dealing skills would NOT be fair at all.  I do agree that ripo's, area spells have too much negative effect on our pets making us very low on the damage dealing table.  <P>I still suggest and will hold to it that if you are a BST and wish to go in fighting in a zone where you feel uncomfortable with your pet because of pathing or ubber mobs.  We should be compensated for it.  Any pet class that is petless normally is still 70% effective, where as the BST is dropped to 50% and I would like to see that upped to 70% as the other classes enjoy.   Therefore, allow us to cast our pet buffs on ourself instead of summoning a warder.  Verant can easily code this..  Why do I say this?  If you cast a DOT on yorself is it FULL EFFECT.. NO, because VI has allowed it to be only 60% of it's ability when it's casted on PC's.   The same type of coding can be done with the pet buff.  If we cast it on ourself the % that is transfered to us is will not overpower us and most likely get us up to 70-80% of what we could be with pet.  <P>I believe one gent said the pet buff adds 700AC and 2,000 in hit points.  OK. lets use those numbers (i may be wrong).  You cast this on yourself and you only get a reasonable % of that to you.. To compesate what you have lost in not having your pet, and add double hit as well.   This mean that we lose the DD spell and bash that our pets are capable of doing as well, but then that was the trade off in casting the buff on me and not on pet.   You can make this pet buff NOT stackable with other buffs if we cast it on ourself if that still becomes a "unbalancing" issue.
