ntee unless you are a completely inept, bumbling idiot that you will escape.<P> <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR>I still suggest and will hold to it that if you are a BST and wish to go in fighting in a zone where you feel uncomfortable with your pet because of pathing or ubber mobs. We should be compensated for it.<HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>Suggestion: DON'T FIGHT IN THOSE ZONES!  It's no secret that necromancers, bards, druids are much more comfortable outdoors than indoors.<P> <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR>Any pet class that is petless normally is still 70% effective, where as the BST is dropped to 50% and I would like to see that upped to 70% as the other classes enjoy.<HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>Not sure where you come up with that.  I'm fairly certain the pet is more than 30% of a magician's damage output.<P> <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR>Therefore, allow us to cast our pet buffs on ourself instead of summoning a warder. Verant can easily code this..<HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>Actually, they can't.  Beneficial spells are pet-only, self-only, group-only, AoE, or everyone.  There is no way to have a spell that is self-only and pet-only at the same time.  If it is not self-only and can be cast on the pet, then it can be cast on anyone.<P>Besides, I'm not entirely convinced the pet buff is actually a buff.  I don't think it actually adds HP/AC/levels/etc to the pet, I think it basically creates a new pet.  (I could be wrong, my personal hypothesis).<P> <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR>I believe one gent said the pet buff adds 700AC and 2,000 in hit points. OK. lets use those numbers (i may be wrong). You cast this on yourself and you only get a reasonable % of that to you.. To compesate what you have lost in not having your pet, and add double hit as well. This mean that we lose the DD spell and bash that our pets are capable of doing as well, but the