ills but argue against more offensive skills.  I agree our offense is fine <I>when we can use our pet</I>.<P>  <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR>We are already at 80% of what a monk can do, which is fine with me.<HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>With a pet...<P>  <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR>All I like to see done offensively is just simply redistribute that so that instead of pet+bst=80% monk damage,,, you get 'no pet'+bst=70% monk damage..<HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>I fail to see how your idea for camo, intimidate, or turtle shell offer us more offensive capabilities...<P>  <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR>If you don't want my suggestion of making the pet buff self casting.. FINE..<HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>It's not that I don't want it, but that it cannot be done.<P>  <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR>then just simply make a WHOLE new spell that is a pet buff that protect the pet from those problems.<HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>Excellent suggestion.  Magicians already received a starting step along this road with their fear immunity spell for their pets.  However, I think it would be extremely difficult to program and there would be balance issues.  Should pets be susceptible to spells in general?  Of course.  Should they not be susceptible to AoE spells?  Might be overpowering in some situations.  Should pets be totally immune to spells from ubermobs?  I could see a single group of beastlords killing many ubermobs with no risk.  Should pets be immune to ripostes?  Perhaps, but I think this one would be extremely difficult to code, if not impossible.<P>  <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR>As for the goofball that suggest fear kiting, you are so totally wrong. OMG I can't believe someone even suggested that. Why in the hell do you think rogues don't fear kite using ID. It's suicidal!!!!! The odds of it running into other mobs that will agro is not worth the risk. Rogues will only use ID towards the end of the fight when its weaken<HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>Actually, rogues and monks typically don't fear kite because the skill is too unreliable for that purpose.  When they can get it to work it saves them from taking damage while they continue dealing damage...but it cannot be used for fear-kiting as a necromancer/shadowknight/bard does.<P>  <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR>flash of light will not do any good becasue at that point in the game the pet has too much agro for the mob to turn<HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>/cough "/pet back off" /cough<P>  <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR>My pet has gone agro and I was unable to repeatively back him off.<HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>Poor pet control.<P>  <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR>SINCE I have not done ONE point of damage yet my agro is virtually NOTHING, and with the first attack of my pet that mob stops, turns and fights my pet, EVEN tho flash of light has NOT worn off....... NOW explain that?<HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>Control your pet better and park him farther away.<P>  <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR>SO where does this fear kiting you suggest come from? I've played my class for a long time and I've never seen my pet chase and bite a mob running off after flash of light landed?<HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>The poster was referring to your intimidate skill, not to Flash of Light.  Though a limited form of fear kiting is possible with Flash of Light and nukes.<P>  <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR>BTW Tan.. did I not say instead of double attack you could add a built in haste to compensate that..... DOH.. are haste spells not in the game anymore?<HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>I rejected that for the sheer stupidity of the suggestion.  A raiding beastlord will be able to reach (and even pass) the haste cap.  This really offers us nothing for 